{
  "texts": [
    "The noise samples have variance given by σ 2 i = 4R i kT B, i ∈ {0, 1}, where R i denotes the selected resistor corresponding to the input bit [4].",
    "Here, k, T, and B represent the Boltzmann constant, the absolute temperature (in Kelvins), and the signal bandwidth, respectively.",
    "In turn, the n-th received complex baseband sample is given byx n = h s n + w n,(1)where n ∈ {1, 2,..., N }, N denotes the total number of collected samples during the symbol duration, and h is the complex channel coefficient, w n ∼ CN (0, σ 2 w) denotes the additive white Gaussian noise (AWGN), and s n ∼ CN (0, σ 2 i), i ∈ {0, 1}, is the transmitted noise sample with variance σ 2 0, for bit 0, or σ 2 1, for bit 1, where σ 2 w < σ 2 0 < σ 2 1.",
    "In this work, two scenarios for h are considered.",
    "In the first one, it is assumed to be known due to perfect channel estimation within a coherence interval that spans one or more symbols."
  ]
}